ğŸ›  Kubernetes Installation in AWS Bare Metal Using KubeAdm
This guide covers the step-by-step installation of Kubernetes on AWS EC2 instances using KubeAdm.

ğŸ“Œ Prerequisites
âœ… Enable the following ports on all EC2 instances:
22 (SSH)
80 (HTTP)
443 (HTTPS)
6443 (Kubernetes API Server)
ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Install Docker
Run the following commands to install Docker:

sh
Copy
Edit
# Remove existing Docker versions
sudo yum remove docker \
                  docker-client \
                  docker-client-latest \
                  docker-common \
                  docker-latest \
                  docker-latest-logrotate \
                  docker-logrotate \
                  docker-engine

# Install required dependencies
sudo yum install -y yum-utils

# Add Docker repository
sudo yum-config-manager --add-repo https://download.docker.com/linux/centos/docker-ce.repo

# Install Docker
sudo yum install docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin

# Start Docker
sudo systemctl start docker
ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Install cri-dockerd
Kubernetes has discontinued Docker support. The cri-dockerd is required for runtime support.

sh
Copy
Edit
# Install Git
sudo yum install git

# Clone cri-dockerd repository
git clone https://github.com/Mirantis/cri-dockerd.git

# Install Go
sudo yum install go

# Build cri-dockerd (this may take time)
cd cri-dockerd
make cri-dockerd

# Install cri-dockerd
mkdir -p /usr/local/bin
sudo install -o root -g root -m 0755 cri-dockerd /usr/local/bin/cri-dockerd
sudo install packaging/systemd/* /etc/systemd/system

# Configure systemd service
sudo sed -i -e 's,/usr/bin/cri-dockerd,/usr/local/bin/cri-dockerd,' /etc/systemd/system/cri-docker.service

# Reload systemd and enable cri-dockerd service
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable --now cri-docker.socket
ğŸ” Verify cri-dockerd Status
sh
Copy
Edit
# Check running processes
ps -aef | grep cri-dockerd

# Check service logs
systemctl status cri-docker

# Start cri-docker service if not running
sudo systemctl start cri-docker
ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Install KubeAdm, Kubelet, and Kubectl
sh
Copy
Edit
# Disable SELinux
sudo setenforce 0
sudo sed -i 's/^SELINUX=enforcing$/SELINUX=permissive/' /etc/selinux/config
ğŸ“ Configure Kubernetes Repository
sh
Copy
Edit
cat <<EOF | sudo tee /etc/yum.repos.d/kubernetes.repo
[kubernetes]
name=Kubernetes
baseurl=https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.28/rpm/
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://pkgs.k8s.io/core:/stable:/v1.28/rpm/repodata/repomd.xml.key
exclude=kubelet kubeadm kubectl cri-tools kubernetes-cni
EOF
ğŸ“¦ Install Kubernetes Components
sh
Copy
Edit
sudo yum install -y kubelet kubeadm kubectl --disableexcludes=kubernetes
sudo systemctl enable --now kubelet
ğŸ”¹ Step 4: Initialize Kubernetes Cluster (Master Node Only)
Run the following command ONLY on the master node:

sh
Copy
Edit
sudo kubeadm init --cri-socket /var/run/cri-dockerd.sock
ğŸ›  Configure kubectl for Cluster Access
sh
Copy
Edit
mkdir -p $HOME/.kube
sudo cp -i /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf $HOME/.kube/config
sudo chown $(id -u):$(id -g) $HOME/.kube/config
âš ï¸ Note: The above commands should be executed as a regular user, not root.

ğŸ”¹ Step 5: Join Worker Nodes
After running kubeadm init successfully on the master node, it will generate a join command.
Use that command to add worker nodes. Below is an example (Do NOT copy-paste directly):

sh
Copy
Edit
sudo kubeadm join 172.31.34.235:6443 --token zp1y6a.3qvtegpe506jhw3o \
      --discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:65229eb4f20f161cfe52604e44c02349fb1dcdf6c6c65e8f19001c30c1afb027 \
      --cri-socket /var/run/cri-dockerd.sock
ğŸ”¹ Step 6: Install Calico for Networking
To implement networking and network policy, install Calico on the master node:

sh
Copy
Edit
curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.26.1/manifests/calico.yaml -O
kubectl apply -f calico.yaml
ğŸ” Verify Cluster Status
sh
Copy
Edit
kubectl get nodes
This should list all nodes in the cluster with a Ready status.

ğŸ¯ Conclusion
You have successfully installed Kubernetes on AWS Bare Metal using KubeAdm.
This guide covered setting up Docker, cri-dockerd, Kubernetes components, and Calico networking. ğŸš€

